data.name: label_Forward.Text
data.value: Forward Rendering is the traditional rendering method and is mostly associated when using static lighting as lightmaps and lightgrids. This renderer has an extra depth buffer pass, which allows forward rendering to use post processing.

data.name: label_NoRenderer.Text
data.value: For reasons of backwards compatibility Vision also supports running without any renderer node installed. This means that the default forward renderer is used, a single Vision render loop instance is used for the main render context. Note that post processors and advanced effects requiring renderer node-related data can not be used in this case.

data.name: label_Deferred.Text
data.value: Deferred Rendering is a more advanced rendering method than forward. It provides plenty of post processing effects and allows the use of many dynamic lights in a scene. The performance impact is usually higher than for the Forward Renderer and depends in the first place on the screen resolution.

data.name: label_ForwardMobile.Text
data.value: Mobile Forward Rendering is a rendering method designed especially for mobile devices. The main difference to the default Forward Renderer is that dynamic lighting is performed by rendering the dominant light source in the base pass.

data.name: label_RendererDescription.Text
data.value: Choosing the correct renderer for your scene can have a significant impact on performance and visuals. Forward Rendering is mostly associated when using static lighting as lightmaps and lightgrids. Deferred can be used when the scene should contain many dynamic lights.

data.name: label_AdaptiveTM.Text
data.value: This post-processing effect provides functionality for mapping HDR color targets to the valid range of a color display. It can gradually adapt the scene brightness over time based on the brightness, and color parameters color control like saturation, contrast, and brightness settings for HDR render targets. It supports also a simple motion blur effect. This tone mapping component requires HDR to be enabled.

data.name: label_DepthFog.Text
data.value: The depth fog post processor allows you to apply fog to your scene that fades in into the distance. When time of day is enabled this effect is using the fog ranges and the fog color curve defined in the time of day properties.

data.name: label_SSAO.Text
data.value: Screen-Space Ambient Occlusion (SSAO) is a technique to simulate shadowing around the edges of scene object intersections, this helps create a stronger sense of depth in the scene. It is recommended to configure this post processor depending on the scene scale.

data.name: label_Glow.Text
data.value: Glow increases the intensity where light is concentrated. The rendered scene is downscaled, the colors are scaled and biased, and the resulting texture is blurred before being additively applied to the original scene. The glow effect provides best results when HDR is enabled in the renderer settings.

data.name: label_DOF.Text
data.value: Depth of field can be used to simulate the effect of a camera focusing on certain parts of the scene. This has the effect of blurring objects that are not at the focal point, i.e. objects that are either further away or closer than the focal point.

data.name: label_ToneMapping.Text
data.value: Tone mapping is the process of performing color correction and mapping on the rendered image (saturation, brightness, contrast). It is also possible to use color grading by using a lookup table. This post processor also contains a screen motion blur feature.

data.name: label_PostProcessorDescription.Text
data.value: Post Processing effects are an important part of the modern rendering pipeline. Please select which post processors you would like to use in your scene. You can add, remove and edit each post processor in the renderer components dialog.

data.name: label_TOD.Text
data.value: When working on an outdoor scene it is possible to enable a special type of lighting system to simulate the natural cycles of day and night. The time of day system also has many attributes for controlling atmospheric conditions such as fog and skys which when combined create a convincing atmosphere.

data.name: label_LightingDescription.Text
data.value: Vision provides various features to create convincing lighting in your scene. For outdoor scenes you can use the time of day system that can be incorporated with sun light, dynamic shadows and various other effects.
